Supporting Document
Anonymized Case Snapshots: Between-Session Execution Gap

Purpose
These anonymized snapshots illustrate the recurring pattern addressed in the proposed HBR article: strong in-session insight paired with weak between-session execution infrastructure.

Case Snapshot 1
Role Context
SVP-level technology leader preparing for C-level succession conversation in a complex stakeholder environment.

Initial Pattern
- Coaching sessions were high quality and strategy-rich.
- Between sessions, the executive tracked no consistent market or stakeholder signals.
- Preparation for high-stakes conversations was inconsistent and heavily reactive.
- Action commitments were broad and difficult to verify.

Intervention
- Established 6 weekly role-critical signals across stakeholder sentiment, role-scope expectations, and external market narrative.
- Introduced one-page prep briefs for all high-stakes conversations.
- Replaced generic action items with explicit commitments: owner, due date, artifact, and review point.

Observed Changes Over 8 Weeks
- Prep completion moved from sporadic to consistent before priority conversations.
- Coaching sessions shifted from re-establishing context to advancing decisions.
- Stakeholder conversations showed greater message consistency and clearer asks.
- Executive self-reported lower cognitive load and higher confidence entering high-stakes meetings.

What This Illustrates
The major gain came from execution continuity between sessions, not from increasing session volume.

Case Snapshot 2
Role Context
Experienced executive leader in transition to a broader enterprise role with new political terrain and decision rights.

Initial Pattern
- Strong conceptual clarity in-session.
- Follow-through fragmentation across multiple concurrent priorities.
- Repeated context reset consumed coaching time.
- Stakeholder interactions lacked a consistent narrative arc.

Intervention
- Defined a prioritized signal taxonomy: team, peer, sponsor, and enterprise-level indicators.
- Added pre-conversation preparation standards for board- and C-suite-adjacent interactions.
- Implemented a weekly accountability loop with visible commitment tracking.

Observed Changes Over 10 Weeks
- Fewer repeated context resets in coaching sessions.
- Improved continuity across stakeholder meetings and clearer escalation decisions.
- Higher completion of strategic commitments tied to role-transition objectives.
- Coach-reported increase in session depth due to reduced administrative recap.

What This Illustrates
Session quality alone was insufficient. The key variable was between-session operating discipline.

Cross-Case Insights
1. Insight does not predict execution without structured follow-through.
2. Lightweight preparation protocols outperform ad hoc reflection.
3. Visibility into a small number of critical signals improves leadership judgment.
4. Accountability quality matters more than accountability volume.

Limitations
- Cases are practitioner observations, not randomized controlled trials.
- Causal attribution is directional and bounded by field context.
- Sector and role-specific factors may affect transferability.

Confidentiality Note
All identifying details have been removed or generalized. The snapshots are intended to illustrate repeatable patterns rather than disclose client-specific information.